📊 Dataset Description: Employee Promotion Dataset

This dataset contains employee-level information collected from an organization and is primarily used to predict whether an employee will be promoted or not.
It is a binary classification problem commonly used in machine learning and HR analytics.

Total records: 54,808 employees

Total features: 13 columns

Target variable: is_promoted

🧩 Column-wise Description
🆔 Identifiers

employee_id
Unique ID assigned to each employee.

🏢 Employee Profile

department
Department in which the employee works
(e.g., Sales & Marketing, Operations, Technology)

region
Office region or location code of the employee
(e.g., region_7, region_22)

education
Highest education qualification
(Bachelor's, Master's & above, etc.)

gender
Gender of the employee (m or f)

age
Age of the employee in years

📋 Recruitment & Experience

recruitment_channel
Source through which the employee was hired
(sourcing, other, referred)

length_of_service
Total years the employee has worked in the organization

no_of_trainings
Number of training programs attended by the employee

⭐ Performance Indicators

previous_year_rating
Performance rating from the previous year
(Scale: 1 to 5, may contain missing values)

avg_training_score
Average score achieved in training programs

awards_won
Whether the employee won any award

0 → No

1 → Yes

🎯 Target Variable

is_promoted
Indicates whether the employee was promoted

0 → Not Promoted

1 → Promoted

📌 Key Characteristics of the Dataset

Imbalanced dataset
Very few employees are promoted compared to non-promoted ones.

Mixed data types

Categorical: department, region, education, gender

Numerical: age, training score, service length

Real-world HR problem
Used for promotion prediction, talent management, and performance analysis.

🧠 Typical Use Cases

Employee promotion prediction

Classification algorithms (Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest, XGBoost)

Handling imbalanced classes

Feature engineering & model evaluation
